1
00:01:29,320 --> 00:01:32,870
<i>On January 4th 1969
Professor Jan Moll was the first</i>

2
00:01:33,040 --> 00:01:35,790
<i>to attempt a heart transplant
in Poland</i>

3
00:01:35,920 --> 00:01:38,870
<i>The patient died
on the operating table</i>

4
00:02:14,880 --> 00:02:18,870
POLISH ATTEMPT HEART TRANSPLANT

5
00:02:31,960 --> 00:02:35,870
Prof. Moll was not prepared.

6
00:02:40,120 --> 00:02:44,590
He decided to operate without
the necessary knowledge

7
00:02:45,040 --> 00:02:48,070
to have success.

8
00:02:48,400 --> 00:02:52,400
A Lukasz Palkowski film

9
00:02:52,400 --> 00:02:56,440
MOLL KILLS PATIENT
ON THE OPERATING TABLE

10
00:02:56,920 --> 00:02:59,480
Prof. Moll, did you realise

11
00:03:00,280 --> 00:03:04,790
that a procedure
on, such a vital organ as, the heart

12
00:03:05,200 --> 00:03:07,790
may alter the recipient's personality?

13
00:03:08,720 --> 00:03:11,070
Maybe it was a risky choice,

14
00:03:11,240 --> 00:03:15,230
but the only one which
gave the patient a chance to survive.

15
00:03:15,400 --> 00:03:20,110
- but leaving no chance for the donor...
- He was pronounced brain dead!

16
00:03:20,640 --> 00:03:23,910
The Poles are jealous even
of one others failures.

17
00:03:25,400 --> 00:03:27,310
<i>Based on a true story</i>

18
00:04:29,560 --> 00:04:32,310
<i>Warsaw, 1983</i>

19
00:05:12,080 --> 00:05:15,510
35 minutes. Too long.

20
00:05:27,040 --> 00:05:30,110
GODS
<i>- Religa.</i>

21
00:05:34,520 --> 00:05:36,980
- What do we have?
- 42, chest pain,

22
00:05:37,160 --> 00:05:40,230
cold extremities,
pulse 115, pressure...

23
00:05:40,400 --> 00:05:43,470
- Let me osculate.
- Blood pressure 72/40,

24
00:05:43,840 --> 00:05:46,270
ECG with infarction signs.

25
00:05:48,840 --> 00:05:50,830
Acute systolic murmur.

26
00:05:51,520 --> 00:05:55,300
We're operating! Prepare the OR,
and call the perfusionist.

27
00:05:56,640 --> 00:05:57,790
Let's go.

28
00:06:06,240 --> 00:06:10,310
- The old man will have your balls.
- Have you seen his coronarography?

29
00:06:10,480 --> 00:06:14,630
- We have to open him up.
- maybe we should take him in for observation?

30
00:06:21,400 --> 00:06:24,550
Pulse is accelerating,
the pressure's barely holding.

31
00:06:24,680 --> 00:06:28,070
- Krysia, call the old man.

32
00:06:29,800 --> 00:06:35,000
Krysia, Krysia! Someone has to finish after me
in the pathology.

33
00:06:36,560 --> 00:06:39,470
Zbyszek, What the fuck are we doing?
He doesn't stand a chance.

34
00:06:40,000 --> 00:06:42,510
Turn that beeper up!

35
00:06:44,440 --> 00:06:46,150
Using the pump?

36
00:06:46,320 --> 00:06:49,630
- Where is the perfusionist?
- He's changing. - Time.

37
00:06:53,240 --> 00:06:55,700
- Where've you been?
- In the middle of the night? At home!

38
00:06:56,240 --> 00:06:59,230
- What's this?
- Acute mitral regurgitation.

39
00:06:59,400 --> 00:07:01,630
- Probably.
- And the boss?

40
00:07:01,800 --> 00:07:04,950
Krysia's trying to reach him.
We can either try to help

41
00:07:06,200 --> 00:07:10,710
or wait till he dies.
I'll need a vein and a valve!

42
00:07:11,240 --> 00:07:13,550
The valves are locked.

43
00:07:32,240 --> 00:07:34,270
We can start the briefing.

44
00:07:40,080 --> 00:07:42,910
Where is Dr. Religa?

45
00:07:50,480 --> 00:07:52,550
The report from the night shift...

46
00:07:52,720 --> 00:07:56,830
At 11.15 pm a patient brought in
with a myocardial infarction,

47
00:07:57,000 --> 00:08:00,830
- a distinct murmur at the heart apex.
- A valve.

48
00:08:02,960 --> 00:08:05,550
He didn't operate, did he?

49
00:08:19,120 --> 00:08:21,870
The professor wants to see you.

50
00:08:22,280 --> 00:08:24,150
So he sends coffee?

51
00:08:26,680 --> 00:08:29,630
- Check his hourly diuresis.
- Why did you

52
00:08:29,800 --> 00:08:32,030
decide to operate on your own?

53
00:08:32,240 --> 00:08:34,630
I was on duty.

54
00:08:34,800 --> 00:08:37,310
My dear colleague...

55
00:08:37,800 --> 00:08:40,190
- In my clinic...
- He would have died.

56
00:08:40,960 --> 00:08:43,950
- Don't interrupt!
- We couldn't reach you.

57
00:08:46,640 --> 00:08:50,990
You've broken all the rules.
Without my consent, in ECC,

58
00:08:51,160 --> 00:08:53,720
not to mention the break-in.

59
00:08:55,000 --> 00:08:57,640
- I had to operate.
- Thank you.

60
00:09:07,560 --> 00:09:11,390
So far, the patient is stable.

61
00:09:13,360 --> 00:09:15,630
Go home and rest.

62
00:09:15,840 --> 00:09:18,710
Someone will fill in for you.

63
00:09:35,520 --> 00:09:37,870
What's up, Zbyszek? How was it?

64
00:09:40,880 --> 00:09:45,070
- Ewa, what are you doing here?
- You lost your steloscope again.

65
00:09:45,240 --> 00:09:48,630
It's called a stethoscope.
Tell me...

66
00:09:48,800 --> 00:09:51,790
what would I do without you?

67
00:09:52,280 --> 00:09:55,000
Don't smoke, you'll lose stamina.

68
00:09:56,960 --> 00:10:00,230
Doctor, don't make passes
at our patient.

69
00:10:00,680 --> 00:10:03,710
- Go to sleep.
- Hang on there.

70
00:10:06,600 --> 00:10:09,110
- Walking or riding?
- Riding.

71
00:10:09,560 --> 00:10:12,150
Hold on.

72
00:11:39,240 --> 00:11:44,790
I've never heard anyone in Poland
share their professional insights.

73
00:11:50,480 --> 00:11:53,310
- Jan Moll.
- Zbigniew Religa.

74
00:11:54,800 --> 00:12:00,550
Our guest here, assisted his brother
during the first heart transplant in the World.

75
00:12:01,360 --> 00:12:04,750
A year later, I did it here.

76
00:12:04,960 --> 00:12:07,230
They made history...

77
00:12:07,960 --> 00:12:10,420
And you almost got crucified!

78
00:12:12,560 --> 00:12:15,830
- Have you been in the U.S. for long?
- In total...

79
00:12:16,000 --> 00:12:20,230
- two years.
- It may be more difficult for you here.

80
00:12:51,960 --> 00:12:54,600
- Were you bored?
- Only at the end.

81
00:12:55,840 --> 00:12:58,230
Remember how many times the DA

82
00:12:59,320 --> 00:13:02,670
asked us to open skulls
in order to certify death,

83
00:13:02,840 --> 00:13:06,390
and a few days later
the patient would go home?

84
00:13:06,960 --> 00:13:11,430
- Were those miracles?
- Surgeons don't wait for miracles.

85
00:13:14,200 --> 00:13:18,030
We have no right to experiments
which, if unsuccessful,

86
00:13:18,560 --> 00:13:20,910
could take even a week of life away.

87
00:13:23,800 --> 00:13:27,230
Could you cope with that?
Let's go get a drink.

88
00:13:38,120 --> 00:13:40,990
No one else wants to go
to that shithole?

89
00:13:41,160 --> 00:13:43,950
Will you get
your own clinic in Warsaw?

90
00:13:44,080 --> 00:13:47,070
Staszek, I've got a family,
I won't take your clinic.

91
00:13:47,240 --> 00:13:50,950
- You could do what you want.
- I do it anyway.

92
00:13:51,160 --> 00:13:53,620
That's why I'm talking to you.

93
00:13:56,840 --> 00:13:58,830
I need some fresh air.

94
00:14:00,680 --> 00:14:03,240
- Goodnight.
- Goodnight.

95
00:14:04,880 --> 00:14:07,710
Zbyszek! Zabrze is beautiful!

96
00:14:12,440 --> 00:14:15,870
Hello.

97
00:14:16,480 --> 00:14:17,960
Good evening.

98
00:14:26,840 --> 00:14:28,510
No, thanks. I don't smoke.

99
00:14:32,400 --> 00:14:36,630
- Marian Zembala, Andrzej Bochenek.
- Religa. Zbyszek.

100
00:14:36,760 --> 00:14:38,750
Good evening.

101
00:14:39,760 --> 00:14:43,990
- We've seen you talking to Moll, sir.
- We're on first name basis.

102
00:14:44,160 --> 00:14:47,310
Did you talk to Moll
about transplants?

103
00:14:48,080 --> 00:14:49,950
About rejection.

104
00:14:50,120 --> 00:14:52,710
We've been analysing his operation.

105
00:14:53,800 --> 00:14:57,550
- And you found it successful?
- We stopped at rejections.

106
00:14:58,800 --> 00:15:02,550
But even that was too much.
They want to get rid of us so bad,

107
00:15:02,720 --> 00:15:05,750
- they're sending us for internships.
- Where?

108
00:15:05,920 --> 00:15:10,790
- England for me, Holland for him.
- Congratulations. I was in the US.

109
00:15:11,320 --> 00:15:14,550
This is the way it is. The old are too scared,
and the young aren't allowed.

110
00:15:16,080 --> 00:15:19,550
Just make sure you come back,
don't leave me alone with them.

111
00:15:23,400 --> 00:15:25,230
How was the congress?

112
00:15:27,280 --> 00:15:31,060
- We'll be done before your read it.
- Thank you, doctor.

113
00:15:31,200 --> 00:15:34,790
- How are you Ewka?
- I'm good, Zbyszek. - Ewka!

114
00:15:35,560 --> 00:15:38,150
- How are you feeling?
- Poorly.

115
00:15:38,320 --> 00:15:40,750
- Where are you going?
- To get cut.

116
00:15:41,560 --> 00:15:44,950
Do you remember, I told about those operations.
They're easy.

117
00:15:45,560 --> 00:15:47,990
- It's something else I'm worried about.
- What is it?

118
00:15:48,160 --> 00:15:50,350
That I'll be naked in there.

119
00:15:51,800 --> 00:15:54,310
Don't worry, I'll close my eyes.

120
00:15:55,600 --> 00:15:58,430
- Watch him for me.
- Watch Teddy, got it.

121
00:16:00,920 --> 00:16:02,630
Ewa...

122
00:16:05,840 --> 00:16:09,070
- On stage, but doesn't speak?
- A mime.

123
00:16:10,360 --> 00:16:13,080
I thought it was a dog.
Saw.

124
00:16:14,560 --> 00:16:16,790
What's with the silence?

125
00:16:19,120 --> 00:16:22,190
- We're going into circulation.
- Cooling.

126
00:16:23,320 --> 00:16:25,310
- Suction.
- Ready.

127
00:16:29,400 --> 00:16:32,150
- Let's open the heart.

128
00:16:34,800 --> 00:16:36,470
Hook.

129
00:16:42,680 --> 00:16:45,110
- Oh, Ewa...
- What is it?

130
00:16:47,080 --> 00:16:49,830
- What is it?
- Fuck!

131
00:16:50,000 --> 00:16:53,070
Take a look.
It's not your typical TOF.

132
00:16:53,200 --> 00:16:56,510
- The ventricle is enlarged.
- Acquired atresia.

133
00:16:56,720 --> 00:16:59,710
- We can't do it all.
- You want to leave it?

134
00:16:59,880 --> 00:17:03,310
- Her heart won't make it.
- We've got no choice.

135
00:17:03,840 --> 00:17:07,150
First let's close
the ventricular defect.

136
00:17:07,320 --> 00:17:10,390
Then widen the pulmonary valve.

137
00:17:12,000 --> 00:17:13,790
It has to work!

138
00:17:14,280 --> 00:17:16,070
Tweezers.

139
00:17:18,400 --> 00:17:21,670
36 degrees. After reperfusion.

140
00:17:23,440 --> 00:17:26,950
- The patient is warm.
- Prepare to go out of ECC.

141
00:17:28,240 --> 00:17:31,110
- Reducing cardiac output.
- How much?

142
00:17:31,280 --> 00:17:33,630
1.5... 1.5 litres.

143
00:17:34,520 --> 00:17:36,270
Gently.

144
00:17:50,320 --> 00:17:52,390
Breathing.

145
00:17:54,640 --> 00:17:57,100
Stop circulation.

146
00:18:06,440 --> 00:18:08,870
What's wrong? What is it?

147
00:18:09,880 --> 00:18:11,990
Fuck... we've got hypoxia.

148
00:18:13,640 --> 00:18:16,310
Keep working, girl. More oxygen.

149
00:18:20,800 --> 00:18:23,190
Zbyszek... let's go back to ECC.

150
00:18:26,760 --> 00:18:31,470
Asystole, again.
She has to manage on her own.

151
00:18:32,040 --> 00:18:35,670
- More adrenaline!
- I can increase it, but it won't help.

152
00:18:35,880 --> 00:18:38,110
- Do it!
- It won't help.

153
00:18:55,080 --> 00:18:56,990
Work with me, girl!

154
00:18:57,160 --> 00:18:58,640
Keep working!

155
00:19:07,880 --> 00:19:11,510
Are you crazy? She could get infected,
put on new ones!

156
00:20:53,320 --> 00:20:55,310
The missus?

157
00:20:57,560 --> 00:21:01,030
- Excuse me?
- Did you mess up or your missus?

158
00:21:01,920 --> 00:21:03,790
God.

159
00:21:06,320 --> 00:21:08,390
Then let it go.

160
00:21:11,040 --> 00:21:12,550
I can't.

161
00:21:12,680 --> 00:21:16,310
You can't force anyone to stay.
The heart won't listen.

162
00:21:20,640 --> 00:21:23,150
We'll see about that.

163
00:22:01,320 --> 00:22:03,390
I didn't...

164
00:22:05,000 --> 00:22:08,550
I didn't make any mistakes.

165
00:22:13,640 --> 00:22:16,200
There was no other way to do it.

166
00:22:19,960 --> 00:22:22,790
I had to try.

167
00:22:27,240 --> 00:22:31,750
Having diagnosed pulmonary atresia,
Why didn't you stop the operation?

168
00:22:32,960 --> 00:22:36,630
There was no other option.
What would you have done?

169
00:22:39,400 --> 00:22:44,710
You had a variety
of options to choose from.

170
00:22:44,840 --> 00:22:46,950
For example?

171
00:22:48,160 --> 00:22:53,790
If you had stopped, would the patient
have survived?

172
00:22:55,160 --> 00:22:57,030
No.

173
00:22:57,240 --> 00:23:00,230
What was
the direct cause of death?

174
00:23:01,880 --> 00:23:04,270
Electromechanical dissociation

175
00:23:04,480 --> 00:23:07,950
caused by end-stage
heart damage in this disease.

176
00:23:08,120 --> 00:23:11,230
We didn't overcome
the vascular resistance

177
00:23:11,400 --> 00:23:15,440
due to the underdeveloped
pulmonary vessels.

178
00:23:15,640 --> 00:23:19,750
The heart didn't start beating,
after the defects have been removed.

179
00:23:21,880 --> 00:23:24,070
You've convinced me.

180
00:23:24,240 --> 00:23:26,750
- But not me.
- Come on...

181
00:23:27,800 --> 00:23:30,390
It was too late for the surgery...

182
00:23:31,960 --> 00:23:36,550
Dr Religa didn't make any mistakes.
He had to try.

183
00:23:37,480 --> 00:23:40,950
That girl's life
must have been unbearable.

184
00:23:42,400 --> 00:23:45,310
The smallest effort
could have killed her.

185
00:23:45,880 --> 00:23:50,470
Doctor, thank you for coming
to the Ethics Committee.

186
00:23:52,880 --> 00:23:55,340
There was...

187
00:23:55,840 --> 00:23:59,590
one solution
that could have saved her.

188
00:24:00,240 --> 00:24:02,990
Care to enlighten us?

189
00:24:03,640 --> 00:24:06,150
A heart transplant.

190
00:24:07,640 --> 00:24:10,310
You must be joking.

191
00:24:10,480 --> 00:24:14,470
You'd be willing
to experiment on a child?

192
00:24:15,560 --> 00:24:20,070
I don't know why you,
cardiologists, think that you're gods.

193
00:24:20,240 --> 00:24:23,230
Do you know any other way
we could've saved her?

194
00:24:24,000 --> 00:24:26,310
I repeat:

195
00:24:26,640 --> 00:24:30,390
we are investigating
a child's death.

196
00:24:30,560 --> 00:24:34,550
That's right.
It was also my child... dear colleague.

197
00:24:38,560 --> 00:24:40,510
Thank you.

198
00:25:24,960 --> 00:25:26,630
Wait...just a second...

199
00:25:31,480 --> 00:25:34,550
I have to go to Warsaw.
I won't be long.

200
00:25:36,160 --> 00:25:38,750
If you go, I'll divorce you.

201
00:25:55,760 --> 00:25:58,750
I have to.
I'll be back in the evening.

202
00:26:34,640 --> 00:26:37,550
A very interesting case.
Let's go.

203
00:26:38,640 --> 00:26:40,510
Professor!

204
00:26:41,400 --> 00:26:45,390
- Good to see you're enjoying your holiday.
- I know.

205
00:26:45,760 --> 00:26:49,150
We must launch
a heart transplant program.

206
00:26:54,320 --> 00:26:56,880
Continue gentlemen, I'll catch up in a minute.

207
00:26:59,880 --> 00:27:03,310
We've got the gear,
the people, the technology...

208
00:27:03,480 --> 00:27:07,550
The British have positive results
with cyclosporine.

209
00:27:07,720 --> 00:27:09,670
Let's do this!

210
00:27:15,000 --> 00:27:18,390
- Cutting a beating heart out of...
- A body.

211
00:27:19,200 --> 00:27:21,110
A human being.

212
00:27:22,960 --> 00:27:25,310
It's ethically vague.

213
00:27:25,600 --> 00:27:27,870
The world has no doubts.

214
00:27:28,880 --> 00:27:32,470
I know that, in our country,
the heart is a relic.

215
00:27:32,640 --> 00:27:35,310
But we both know it's a muscle.

216
00:27:36,200 --> 00:27:39,830
Also,the cost of one transplant

217
00:27:40,000 --> 00:27:42,720
equals the cost of three other
operations.

218
00:27:42,880 --> 00:27:45,950
Three lives for one?
Can we afford it?

219
00:27:46,080 --> 00:27:49,110
Let's save them all, Professor!

220
00:27:51,720 --> 00:27:53,950
We don't have enough data.

221
00:27:54,640 --> 00:27:58,910
- We could give life to many people.
- Or false hope.

222
00:27:59,080 --> 00:28:01,800
So you rather wait for a miracle?

223
00:28:03,640 --> 00:28:07,070
Zbyszek... in my clinic

224
00:28:07,960 --> 00:28:11,710
there are only two ways
in which you'd perform a transplant:

225
00:28:12,080 --> 00:28:17,230
Either after my retirement
Or after my death. Basically, the same thing.

226
00:28:18,800 --> 00:28:21,110
Are the fish biting?

227
00:28:36,720 --> 00:28:38,670
Yes, I'm waiting.

228
00:28:39,000 --> 00:28:43,790
Staszek, straight to the point:
my favourite team is Gornik Zabrze...

229
00:28:44,640 --> 00:28:46,870
I'll take that clinic.
- Excuse me ladies, this is a sudden emergency

230
00:29:18,200 --> 00:29:21,390
I was offered my own clinic.

231
00:29:22,240 --> 00:29:24,190
- By Sitkowski?
- No.

232
00:29:24,800 --> 00:29:27,390
By Pasyk, in Zabrze.

233
00:29:30,800 --> 00:29:32,790
You know what?

234
00:29:34,040 --> 00:29:36,150
I don't like it here anymore.

235
00:29:41,640 --> 00:29:45,390
I can't go with you.
We'll lose the apartment.

236
00:29:45,520 --> 00:29:48,750
- I have to go.
- What about me?

237
00:29:48,960 --> 00:29:52,670
My research, my students?
Doesn't that count?

238
00:29:52,880 --> 00:29:55,830
You're saying I should say no?

239
00:29:56,000 --> 00:30:00,070
- You could've asked, at least.
- I'm asking.

240
00:30:03,320 --> 00:30:05,630
No, you're not.

241
00:30:25,120 --> 00:30:29,550
It's one of the more disappointing
surprises in my career.

242
00:30:33,240 --> 00:30:37,710
I don't know what I'd do
if I was offered a clinic.

243
00:30:39,040 --> 00:30:41,760
Especially because I have one already.

244
00:30:43,960 --> 00:30:48,230
- But I'm afraid your ambitions...
- The ambitions that you awoke

245
00:30:48,760 --> 00:30:50,790
by sending me abroad.

246
00:30:51,080 --> 00:30:55,790
I'm sick of answering questions whether we
operate people here or just dogs?

247
00:30:59,080 --> 00:31:02,150
I've turned a blind eye
to many things...

248
00:31:03,520 --> 00:31:06,790
But this is something
that might finish you off.

249
